<h1 class="nhsuk-heading-xl">What we’re building</h1>

<p class="nhsuk-lead-paragraph">
  A digital service that holds a personalised sickle cell care plan and makes it available — with
  appropriate access controls — to the people who need it during a crisis: clinicians, the patient,
  and their nominated delegate.
</p>

<h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">The centrepiece: an acute crisis view</h2>
<p class="nhsuk-body">
  A single, high-contrast screen a clinician can act on in seconds — usual analgesia and opioid
  tolerance, what to give and how much, allergies and adverse reactions, the patient’s baseline
  observations, escalation, named consultant, pregnancy flag and emergency contacts. Printable and
  portable.
</p>

<h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">Designed for accountability and trust</h2>
<ul class="nhsuk-list nhsuk-list--bullet">
  <li>Three roles: healthcare professionals (NHS sign-in), patients, and nominated delegates (e.g. next of kin).</li>
  <li>A patient-facing log of <strong>who has accessed their plan</strong> — transparency by design.</li>
  <li>Care-plan versioning and “last updated by”, so changes are attributable.</li>
  <li>Research consent capture, an episode Friends &amp; Family Test, and free-text feedback.</li>
  <li>A full audit trail, including session duration, to support compliance and improvement.</li>
</ul>

<div class="nhsuk-inset-text">
  <p>A working <strong>prototype</strong> has been built to make this tangible for the partnership and
  tender. It runs on synthetic data only and is not a medical device. The production service —
  with NHS Care Identity sign-in, assured information governance and hosting — is what the
  appointed delivery partner will build.</p>
</div>

